            <abstract>
                <p>Magic prayer against the demon Tǝgrǝtyā, who is called ‘Dǝgrǝtyā’ in <ref type="mss" corresp="EMIP02043#ms_i6"/>.
                    According to <bibl><ptr target="bm:Strelcyn1972Wellcome"/><citedRange unit="page">52</citedRange></bibl> 
                    following <bibl><ptr target="bm:Guidi1935Vocabolario2nd"/><citedRange unit="page">327</citedRange></bibl>,
                    ‘Tǝgrǝtyā’ (also: ‘Tǝgridā’) is a demon or ‘devil who stays in lonely places and causes epilepsy’. The verbal plural forms in 
                    <ref type="mss" corresp="EMIP02043#ms_i6"/> and <ref type="mss" corresp="ANLcr66#ms_i4"/> are possibly 
                    grammatically incongruent forms which evolved because of the omission of entities, which have been named before or through
                    the common use in magic prayers, which are normally directed against various demonic entities.</p>
            </abstract>
